dragonca ... @yahoo.com.au wrote

<QUOTE PREVIOUSPOST="
> &quot;blah blah blah to achieve optimum results&quot;.
> This is one that's had me a little confused for a while
> now...'-imum' forms the noun; '-imal' forms the adjective, right?

> Is optimum, above, being used in a nounal or adjectival sense?
">

This usage of "optimum" is adjectival because the word madifies
"results". Nouns often function as adjectives in English.

<QUOTE PREVIOUSPOST="
> I would posit that it's describing the results, ergo, optimal
> should be used. On the other hand, The MacQ tells me that
> optimum is used as a noun (1st def.) and as an adjective
> (2nd def.). Optimal is only defined as an adjective.

> Any chance some nice soul could provide me with a few examples, or
> let me know if I've got it right:
">

If the writer/speaker means by "optimum results" a specific set of
results that have been stipulated as the "best possible known results
in this situation", then it's okay. If the writer/speaker means the
"best possible unknown results in this situation", then it should be
"optimal".

IOW, I would say that "optimum results" indicates a known set of best
results but that "optimal results" indicates an unknown set of best
results. Both in specific circumstances, however.

<QUOTE PREVIOUSPOST="
> I'd like to buy the maximum available. (Can maximum exist on its
> own here, or must it be tied to a concrete noun - the maximum
> available of *what*?)
">

Yes. It's a noun modified by the adjective "available".

<QUOTE PREVIOUSPOST="
> The quality of this chocolate is maximal.
">

Yes, "This is maximal quality chocolate". Not a pretty sentence, but
grammatically and semantically correct.

<QUOTE PREVIOUSPOST="
> Once you've reached the optimal temperature, restart the process.
> This temperature is optimum.
">

I wouldn't use both "optimal" and "optimum" to describe the same
temperature. Choose one and stick with it.

<QUOTE PREVIOUSPOST="
> But maximal and optimum are both objects of 'to be';
">

They are complements of the "be" verb; they are predicate adjectives in
the sentences "This is {maximal/optimum}". To make "optimum" a noun
(and a predicate nominative but not an object of the copula, which is
not a transitive verb and so cannot have a direct or indirect object
but only a complement), you'd need to say "This is the optimum".

<QUOTE PREVIOUSPOST="
> can an object of a verb be an adjective?
">

Yes and no: "John gave Mary red roses for their wedding anniversary,
but for St Patrick's Day, her gave her green". "Green" is an adjective
in this ellipitcal sentence: "roses" has been elided.

<QUOTE PREVIOUSPOST="
> I'm thinking that 'maximal' is describing the *quality* of the
> chocolate, wheras 'optimum' is an equivalent of temperature
> (temperature = optimum;
">

It depends on whether "optimum" is used as an adjective or a noun.

<QUOTE PREVIOUSPOST="
> I'm not sure what the correct terms are for describing this
> grammatically)...
">

I'm not sure either, but I don't think it matters much. Well, at least
not to me it doesn't.

